statement.p:
Find the pivot positions and pivot columns of this matrix
      A = \amat{
      0   -7   -4   2 ;
      2   4   6   12 ;
      3   1   -1   -2
      }.

solution.p:
We saw in this  that a row echelon form of the matrix is
        \amat{1 2 3 6; 0 1 2 4; 0 0 10 30}.
        The pivot positions of A are the entries that become pivots in a row echelon form; they are marked in red below:
        \def\r{\color{red}}\amat{
        \r0   -7   -4   2 ;
        2   \r4   6   12 ;
        3   1   \r-1   -2
        }.
        The first, second, and third columns are pivot columns.



    \amat{ 2 {10} {-1} ;3 {15} 2}
    \quad\xrightarrow{R_1=R_1\div 2}\quad
    &\amat{\color{red}1 5 {-\frac 12}; 3 {15} 2}
    &&\color{blue}\text{(Step 1b)}


    {}\quad\xrightarrow{R_2=R_2-3R_1}\quad
    &\amat{1 5 {-\frac 12}; \color{red}0 0 \frac72}
    &&\color{blue}\text{(Step 1c)}


    {}\quad\xrightarrow{R_2=R_2\times\frac 27}\quad
    &\amat{1 5 {-\frac 12}; 0 0 \color{red}1}
    &&\color{blue}\text{(Step 2b)}


    {}\quad\xrightarrow{R_1=R_1+\frac 12R_2}\quad
    &\amat{1 5 \color{red}0; 0 0 1}
    &&\color{blue}\text{(Step 2c)}


This row reduced matrix corresponds to the inconsistent system

  \syseq{x + 5y = 0; \. \+ 0 = 1\rlap.}

subsection.p:
In other words, the row reduced matrix of an inconsistent system looks like this:
    \amat{
    1  0  \star,  \star,  \color{red}0 ;
    0  1  \star,  \star,  \color{red}0 ;
    0  0  0  0  \color{red}1
    }

We have discussed two classes of matrices so far:



    When the reduced row echelon form of a matrix has a pivot in every non-augmented column, then it corresponds to a system with a unique solution:
    \amat{1 0 0 1; 0 1 0 -2; 0 0 1 3}
    \quad\xrightarrow{\text{translates to}}\quad
    \syseq{x \+ \. \+ \. = 1;
    \. \+ y \+ \. = -2;
    \. \+ \. \+ z = 3\rlap.}




    When the reduced row echelon form of a matrix has a pivot in the last (augmented) column, then it corresponds to a system with a no solutions:

      \amat{1 5 0; 0 0 1}\quad\xrightarrow{\text{translates to}}\quad
      \syseq{x + 5y = 0; \. \+ 0 = 1\rlap.}



What happens when one of the non-augmented columns lacks a pivot?  This is the subject of .

statement.p:
Solve the linear system

          \syseq{2x + y + 12z = 1; x + 2y + 9z = -1}

        using row reduction.

solution.p:


    \amat{2 1 12 1; 1 2 9 -1}
    \quad\xrightarrow{R_1 \longleftrightarrow R_2}\quad
    &\amat{\color{red}1 2 9 -1; 2 1 12 1}
    &&\color{blue}\text{(Optional)}


    {}\quad\xrightarrow{R_2=R_2-2R_1}\quad
    &\amat{1 2 9 -1; \color{red}0 -3 -6 3}
    &&\color{blue}\text{(Step 1c)}


    {}\quad\xrightarrow{R_2=R_2\div -3}\quad
    &\amat{1 2 9 -1; 0 \color{red}1 2 -1}
    &&\color{blue}\text{(Step 2b)}


    {}\quad\xrightarrow{R_1=R_1-2R_2}\quad
    &\amat{1 \color{red}0 5 1; 0 1 2 -1}
    &&\color{blue}\text{(Step 2c)}


This row reduced matrix corresponds to the linear system

  \syseq{x + 5z = 1; y + 2z = -1\rlap.}

In what sense is the system solved?  We will see in .
